.\" c2i.1 - manpage for clipboard-to-imagefile (c2i)
.TH C2I 1 "2026-03-13" "c2i 1.2.0" "User Commands"
.SH NAME
c2i \- save clipboard PNG image to a timestamped file
.SH SYNOPSIS
.B c2i
.RB [ \-c
.RI [ quality ]]
.RB [ \-p ]
.RB [ \-q | \-v ]
.RI [ output_dir ]
.br
.B c2i
.RB [ \-h | \-V ]
.SH DESCRIPTION
.B c2i
reads a PNG image from the X11 clipboard and writes it to a timestamped file.
The output filename has the form:
.PP
.RS
.IR output_dir /image\- YYYYMMDD \- HHMMSS .png
.RE
.PP
If
.I output_dir
is omitted, files are saved to
.BR /tmp .
.PP
Optionally, the saved image can be compressed with
.BR pngquant (1)
and the resulting file path can be copied back to the clipboard.
.SH OPTIONS
.TP
.BR \-c ", " \-\-compress " [" \fIINT\fR ]
Compress the image using
.BR pngquant (1).
.I INT
sets the lower bound of the quality range (valid: 20\(en100; lower values
produce smaller files).
If
.I INT
is omitted, defaults to
.BR 50 .
Values below 20 are clamped to 20.
.TP
.BR \-p ", " \-\-copy\-path
Copy the absolute file path to the clipboard after saving.
This replaces the image data in the clipboard with text.
.TP
.BR \-v ", " \-\-verbose
Print the output file path to stdout on completion.
This is the default behaviour.
.TP
.BR \-q ", " \-\-quiet
Suppress the output file path.
Status and error messages on stderr are also suppressed.
.TP
.BR \-V ", " \-\-version
Print the program name and version, then exit.
.TP
.BR \-h ", " \-\-help
Display the built\-in help text and exit.
.PP
Short options may be bundled (e.g.\&
.BR \-pc\ 70 ).
.SH EXIT STATUS
.TP
.B 0
Success.
.TP
.B 1
General error: no image in clipboard, missing dependency, invalid directory,
or write failure.
.TP
.B 2
Too many arguments (output directory specified more than once).
.TP
.B 22
Invalid command\-line option.
.SH EXAMPLES
Copy a screen region to the clipboard first (e.g.\& with a screenshot tool),
then:
.TP
Save to /tmp (default):
.B c2i
.TP
Save to the current directory:
.B c2i .
.TP
Save with default compression (quality 50):
.B c2i \-c ~/Pictures
.TP
Save with high compression (quality 30):
.B c2i \-c 30 ~/Pictures
.TP
Save and copy path to clipboard:
.B c2i \-p ~/Documents
.TP
Capture file path in a shell variable:
imgfile=$(
.B c2i
~/Pictures )
.TP
Compress and copy path in one command:
.B c2i \-pc 70 ~/Pictures
.SH ENVIRONMENT
.B c2i
uses the X11 clipboard selection via
.BR xclip (1).
A running X server (or compatible Wayland XWayland bridge) is required.
.PP
Terminal output is colour\-coded when both stdout and stderr are connected
to a terminal.
.SH FILES
.TP
.I /tmp/image\-YYYYMMDD\-HHMMSS.png
Default output location.
.SH DEPENDENCIES
.TP
.BR xclip (1)
Required.
Provides clipboard read/write access.
.TP
.BR pngquant (1)
Optional.
Required only when the
.B \-c
flag is used.
.PP
Install both on Debian/Ubuntu:
.PP
.RS
.B sudo apt install xclip pngquant
.RE
.SH BUGS
When
.B \-p
is used, the image data in the clipboard is replaced with the file path
as plain text.
This is by design but may be unexpected.
.SH AUTHORS
Biksu Okusi <biksu@okusi.id>
.SH SEE ALSO
.BR xclip (1),
.BR pngquant (1),
.BR xdotool (1)
